00:12:41,369 --> 00:12:44,890
So let's take a look at what's in our trash.

164
00:12:44,970 --> 00:12:49,953
So these are percentages by weight of materials going to disposal.

165
00:12:50,473 --> 00:12:52,494
That's from the US EPA from 2018.

166
00:12:52,734 --> 00:12:54,335
This is national data.

167
00:12:54,976 --> 00:12:57,377
So it shows that across the nation,

168
00:12:58,754 --> 00:13:02,256
48% of everything that we're throwing away, throwing the trash, is recyclable.

169
00:13:02,276 --> 00:13:05,017
34% of that is compostable.

170
00:13:05,617 --> 00:13:09,880
And 15% of it is potentially reusable or recyclable.

171
00:13:12,601 --> 00:13:15,703
A lot of people wonder, well, what happens to our trash in Medford?

172
00:13:15,723 --> 00:13:16,484
Where does it go?

173
00:13:17,204 --> 00:13:23,328
Well, this is a photograph of the Wheeler Braider Saugus Incinerator in Saugus, not too far from Medford.

174
00:13:24,288 --> 00:13:27,410
And it's a place where all the trash and all the bulk items

175
00:13:27,900 --> 00:13:30,121
go to be incinerated.

176
00:13:33,841 --> 00:13:39,263
There are problems with incineration that have been documented worldwide.

177
00:13:39,943 --> 00:13:42,623
As you can see, the exhaust from this one is particularly bad.

178
00:13:43,404 --> 00:13:45,884
There's a term, toxics in, toxics out.

179
00:13:46,724 --> 00:13:57,267
Whatever you put into a facility like this will come out in one way or another, either in ash or in fumes and exhaust.

180
00:13:59,207 --> 00:14:00,448
What about our recyclables?

181
00:14:00,728 --> 00:14:10,132
So right now, although waste management is the collector, our recyclables are going to the Casella Materials Recovery Facility in Charleston, Massachusetts.

182
00:14:12,173 --> 00:14:14,174
And it looks a little something like this.

183
00:14:14,214 --> 00:14:17,455
This is one of their facilities in another part of the state.

184
00:14:18,671 --> 00:14:21,313
And finally, yard waste composting.

185
00:14:21,373 --> 00:14:29,940
So all of the leaves and Christmas trees that get collected, they go to a yard waste composting facility where they're composted.

186
00:14:29,980 --> 00:14:34,844
There's also about 1600 households that are part of food scraps collection.

187
00:14:35,225 --> 00:14:37,787
Those go to another facility to be composted as well.

188
00:14:38,948 --> 00:14:46,574
So let's take a look at how Medford is doing in terms of what is in Medford's disposal stream across the board.

189
00:14:47,382 --> 00:14:54,528
So for trash, everything that Medford puts out on the curb, 69% of that is trash.

190
00:14:55,669 --> 00:15:05,197
23% of that gets recycled through the single stream recycling and 8% is composted through the yard waste program.

191
00:15:06,160 --> 00:15:20,046
So if we look at that pie and we say, huh, 69% is trash, but then we go back and we look at this EPA pie of what is in the trash, we see that, well, almost none of that is actually garbage.

192
00:15:20,586 --> 00:15:24,327
A lot of it we can recycle, we can compost, and we can even reuse.

193
00:15:24,908 --> 00:15:28,049
So then we go back and we look at this and we see that there's a bit of disconnect.

194
00:15:28,069 --> 00:15:34,091
It seems like there's some opportunity for Medford in terms of what we can do with the things that we throw away.

195
00:15:36,343 --> 00:15:39,144
That's our baseline understanding of the system.

196
00:15:39,244 --> 00:15:51,127
Now we're going to dig into some details in this first topic, basic services of what we're proposing could be a future for Medford's collection services.

197
00:15:52,547 --> 00:15:59,049
So as part of this conversation, we need to talk about who is included in the services moving forward.

198
00:15:59,089 --> 00:16:04,990
So what we're considering for inclusion are one to three unit residences,

199
00:16:05,706 --> 00:16:10,328
K through 12 schools, houses of worship, and all municipal facilities.

200
00:16:12,629 --> 00:16:21,913
So also what we're considering for basic services are the services of trash collection, recycling collection, and compost collection.

201
00:16:22,034 --> 00:16:31,558
In this case, food scraps, food soil paper, and that's tissues and tea bags, small yard trimmings, those sticks and leaves.

202
00:16:32,503 --> 00:16:36,005
And then also seasonal yard trimmings collection for the bigger stuff.

203
00:16:38,207 --> 00:16:44,691
So the foundation of this proposal is really weekly collection of the stuff that rots.

204
00:16:44,991 --> 00:16:45,972
Stuff we compost.

205
00:16:45,992 --> 00:16:47,472
It's called putressables.

206
00:16:48,093 --> 00:16:54,157
This would be collected every week in a 13-gallon cart with a locking lid like you see on the side there.

207
00:16:54,217 --> 00:16:59,680
That's the cart that's currently used by the food scraps composting programs in Medford.

208
00:17:00,215 --> 00:17:03,037
It's approved by the health department because it's rat resistant.

209
00:17:03,938 --> 00:17:06,480
Materials that are accepted, as I mentioned, all food scraps.

210
00:17:06,500 --> 00:17:14,687
We're talking about meat and bones and fish, your turkey carcasses, everything that came out of the ground can go into this stream.

211
00:17:16,549 --> 00:17:24,896
So as a corollary to this, once we have all that stinky stuff out of the trash, part of this proposal is going to every other week trash collection.

212
00:17:26,140 --> 00:17:41,723
trash collected every other week in a 64-gallon cart, the same cart you're using now, there would be the option to pay for more frequent collection if a resident wanted that, or if an entity wanted that, and overflow bags would still be available.

213
00:17:42,223 --> 00:17:54,285
The benefits of this is that you're cutting the number of trucks for trash in half, and the wear and tear and the reduced emissions and the lower cost for the service are benefits.

214
00:17:55,906 --> 00:18:02,868
So we're also considering sticking with every other week recycling, sticking with that 96-gallon cart.

215
00:18:04,269 --> 00:18:07,130
Again, you'd have the option to pay for more service if needed.

216
00:18:08,190 --> 00:18:18,573
But the reason, the rationale behind this is that we've done some research and it turns out that more frequent collection does not mean more recycling happens.

217
00:18:18,713 --> 00:18:20,434
Let me show you what I mean by that.

218
00:18:21,754 --> 00:18:23,915
So this is a comparison of Medford and

219
00:18:24,626 --> 00:18:25,667
various neighbors.

220
00:18:26,628 --> 00:18:28,389
So Medford's the dark blue bar.

221
00:18:28,950 --> 00:18:30,931
The other neighbors are the light blue bars.

222
00:18:31,192 --> 00:18:37,017
